article.headline: S. Illinois 33, Youngstown St. 0
article.story: YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio -- Using a dominant ground game and stifling defense, Southern Illinois (4-2, 3-1) rolled past Youngstown State (2-6, 1-3, Gateway Conference) 33-0 on Saturday in Youngstown, Ohio. Paced by 148 rushing yards from running back Larry Warner, the Salukis dominated possession and the scoreboard from the onset. Southern Illinois opened the scoring just 62 seconds into the game when Joe Allaria (10-for-23, 1 touchdown, 1 interception) pulled in a 24-yard pass from quarterback Chris Dieker for a 7-0 edge. It was 14-0 by the end of the quarter thanks to a 52-yard interception return by Ryan Patton and 17-0 at the half thanks to a 42-yard Kyle Dougherty field goal to close the second quarter. Southern Illinois padded its edge with a third-quarter safety and a pair of fourth-quarter touchdown runs, by Warner and Richard White, who finished with 49 rushing yards in the game. Kamryn Keys led the Penguins with 68 of Youngstown State's 70 net rushing yards, while quarterback Dailyn Campbell struggled through a 15-for-29 day, finishing with an interception and four sacks. Brandian Ross led the Youngstown State defense with nine total tackles, while Brandin Jordan had 11 for the Salukis.
